dataset.title: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities, Bear Creek and Pine Creek Forest Restoration Experiment 2006-2019, Cedar River Municipal Watershed, King County, WA

creator.organizationName: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities

abstract.para: Forest managers are increasingly using thinning and other silvicultural manipulations to enhance the ecological values of managed forests. However, most experiments in ecological thinning have been poorly replicated—either within or among sites—making it difficult to generalize about responses to treatments. In this study, we explore variation in vegetation response (changes in plant cover and richness) to three types of treatments replicated four to five times at each of three sites (Bear, Pine, and Pine-N) in the Cedar River Watershed, western Washington. Treatments were (1) gap creation (all trees removed in a 20-m diameter gap centered in the 40 x 40 m experimental unit), (2) spatially structured thinning that preserved the largest trees and removed smaller trees in clumps (30% reduction in basal area), and (3) control. All three sites lie at low elevations (640-710 m) with similar slopes (10-30%) and aspects (S-SW). All were dominated by 65-yr-old Douglas-fir and western hemlock of similar total basal area (75-80/m2/ha) and very low understory cover (0.8-3.5%) and diversity (0.9 -2.0 species/m2). Cover of all vascular plant species was estimated in ~40-60 1-m2 quadrats per experimental unit before and 3 yr after treatment.

Both removal treatments increased plant cover at all sites compared to controls, but the magnitude of increase did not differ between gap creation and thinning. However, responses varied greatly among replicates and sites. In the gap treatment, for example, increases in mean cover ranged from 0.1% to 17.1% among replicates at different sites. Moreover, while gap creation and thinning had a positive effect on understory cover at all three sites, they did not have similar effects on richness. Richness increased at Pine and Pine-N, but declined at Bear.

Although we anticipated stronger responses to treatment in plots with greater understory development, responses relative to initial conditions differed among sites. At Pine and Pine-N, increases in cover and richness were positively correlated with initial values. At Bear, however, there was no correlation between initial cover and change in cover, and plots with greater initial richness showed larger declines in richness. We explore possible explanations for these differing responses. Our results highlight the importance of replicating treatments within and among sites prior to implementing silvicultural manipulations at larger spatial scales.

description.para: Study sites were chosen based on the following criteria: dominance of Tsuga heterophylla, limited tree regeneration, and minimal development of understory vegetation. The full experiment is randomized block design with three blocks (Bear, Pine, and Pine-N) and three treatments (control, thin, and gap) replicated four or five times in each block (Fig. 1). Study was limited to two replicates of each treatment at Bear and Pine. Treatments are defined as follows:

2. Thinned: Approximately 30% of the basal area within each experimental unit (EU) was removed. The largest trees (40% of the basal area) were first marked for retention. Smaller trees were then removed in randomly located circles of 6 m radius with constraints on overlap (Halpern et al. 2009).
3. Gap: All trees within 10 m of the center of each EU were removed (~20% of the basal area).

Trees were felled and yarded to the edges of EUs, then upslope through a corridor to a roadside landing. Treatments were completed in fall/early winter 2006. Operations occurred on snow at Bear, but not at Pine.

Vegetation was sampled along multiple transects in each EU. Three parallel transects 40 m long, spaced 10 m apart were positioned perpendicular to the slope in control and thinned treatments. Every other meter of each transect was sampled using a 1 x 1 m quadrat resulting in 60 quadrats per EU. In gap treatments, 40-m-long transects were oriented SW–NE and SE–NW. Quadrats were spaced at 1 m intervals from the center of the gap, yielding 10 quadrats per transect (9 for SE) and 39 quadrats per EU; 19 fell within the 10-m radius of the gap (“gap opening” in subsequent figures) and 20 in the adjacent forest (“adjacent forest”).

Within each quadrat we estimated cover (%) of each vascular plant species (herbs and shrubs <1.4 m tall) and ground-surface condition including bare ground, fine litter (<10 cm diameter), fresh coarse woody debris (>10 cm; CWD decay classes 1-2), decayed CWD (classes 3-5; Sollins 1982), tree bases, and stumps. In addition, cover of logging slash was estimated in 2007 (first growing season after treatment). For the current study, vegetation data include those collected prior to treatment (2006) and in year 4 (2010).

abstract.para: The City of Seattle SPU Watershed Management Division manages the Cedar River Municipal Watershed (CRMW) under a Habitat Conservation Plan (HCP) that was approved in 2000. This HCP provides an incidental take permit under the Endangered Species Act and effectively allows the City to provide high quality water to the Seattle metropolitan area in exchange for protecting and restoring fish and wildlife habitat in the watershed over the next 50 years. The HCP forest habitat restoration program intends to improve wildlife habitat for federally listed species by achieving three large goals: 1) accelerating the development of second-growth forests toward old-forest structures, 2) increasing wildlife habitat complexity, and 3) facilitating the development of biological diversity. Substantial uncertainty is inherent in these goals. Hence, this MOA will enable collaboration with scientists at the University of Washington to design and install a research experiment that will address key questions that have developed from the implementation of this forest restoration program. This research will be funded initially by a portion of the BPA mitigation fund that the City received in 2003.
